Title: Resilient Management
Author: Lara   Hogan
My Review: There are some nice gems in the book and I really appreciate Lara putting this together in a well structured and concise way. I particularly enjoyed the focus on folk's needs, the framing on a manager's job in the four dimensions (mentoring, coaching, sponsoring and feedback) and reminders about underrepresented groups. I have found other tools (like the RACI matix, or the Tuckman model) outdated, irrelevant and sometimes dangerous. I would have loved more nuanced approach which reflected the nature of organisations as complex adaptive systems. I also felt the book was grounded more in Orange mindset (from the reinventing organisations model) and had hoped it would lean towards Green or Teal.

My Review: This is a fantastic research based resource that is grounded in earlier work by Argyris, Senge or Schein. With a clear structure to promote teaming (Amy's alternative name to working in teams) supported by culture of psychological safety and with plenty of specific examples from across industries this book is an indispensable guide to creating thriving and effective workplaces for the 21st century.

My Review:
This is a fantastic introduction to both DDD and Functional Programming in a very accessible book. Being grounded in a very concrete and coherent example it's really easy to relate to the ideas presented in the book.
If there is anything I felt lacking from the book, it would be a little more examples of tests and driving implementation with tests alongside driving it with the type system.

It gives a useful new vocabulary and a fresh way of looking at organisations. It was certainly an easy and engaging read, the contents very well researched with many insightful stories well woven together.

My Review: It's great story and a wonderful example how lots of tiny little things in life take you towards a great result. Even if Steve feels touch megalomaniac at times (though you can't deny him amazing inventions and great insights into the future). It can be rather inspiring if you have great ideas and want to change the world...

Title: Becoming a Technical Leader
Author: Gerald M. Weinberg

Title: Religa. Biografia najsłynniejszego polskiego kardiochirurga
Author: Dariusz Kortko

Title: Ludzie czy bogowie. 27 rozmów z najsłynniejszymi polskimi lekarzami
Author: Dariusz Kortko
My Review: Amazing insights into the thoughts and lives of great Polish doctors who created the modern Polish medicine. People who looked at their patients holistically, with compassion, brave to experiment and push the boundaries of what was possible.

Title: Coaching for Performance: GROWing Human Potential and Purpose: The Principles and Practice of Coaching and Leadership
Author: John Whitmore

Title: The Nature of Software Development
Author: Ron Jeffries
My Review: One of the best little books about software I read in a long time. A perfect flight-time read with nice illustrations. I wish all people involved in software development had similar clarity about what this whole game is about.

Title: Nonviolent Communication: A Language of Life: Create Your Life, Your Relationships, and Your World in Harmony with Your Values
Author: Marshall B. Rosenberg
My Review: It's a week of reading and a lifetime of practice. An amazing insight into the source of anger, pain and suffering in the world with some humane, compassionate strategies to live in harmony with yourself and the world around you. Sadly Marshall passed away a few days after I have finished reading his legacy. I hope it continues.

Title: Punished by Rewards: The Trouble with Gold Stars, Incentive Plans, A's, Praise, and Other Bribes
Author: Alfie Kohn
My Review: I loved this book. Perhaps it's not the best written book I've read, there is a fair amount of repetition and some heavy cross-referencing including footnotes on footnotes. I imagine it would've been harder to follow them all in a physical book but it was not a problem with a kindle edition. Regardless it's an amazing book and the content is incredibly stimulating. It has challenged many of my own views on rewards, parenting, management and organisational design. The references are incredibly rich and I'm impressed how much research has gone into this book.

Title: The Psychology of Computer Programming
Author: Gerald M. Weinberg
My Review: Fascinating perspective, a view that is very often missing. Amazing how appropriate and applicable ideas from this book are today! Over 25 years later. I wish more people understood the context of programming form the psychological perspective.

Title: Decisive: How to Make Better Decisions
Author: Chip Heath
My Review: "Thinking fast and slow" for beginners. Useful tactics and nice stories.

Title: How Google Works
Author: Eric Schmidt

Title: How to Change the World: Change Management 3.0
Author: Jurgen Appelo

Title: David and Goliath: Underdogs, Misfits and the Art of Battling Giants
Author: Malcolm Gladwell
My Review: Some very interesting stories, some useful ideas. Mostly an entertaining read.

Title: Brain Rules: 12 Principles for Surviving and Thriving at Work, Home, and School
Author: John Medina

Title: Thinking in Systems: A Primer
Author: Donella H. Meadows
My Review: Perhaps it's just a primer, but what a primer! This book has the potential to change your thinking, your world-view, your paradigm. It's a window into a fascinating and important world of systems thinking - one of the best tools I have found so far to start understanding our non-linear, interconnected, complex world.

Title: Mindset: How You Can Fulfil Your Potential
Author: Carol S. Dweck
My Review: While trying to explain every aspect of human behaviour in terms of just two mindsets is perhaps slightly too simplistic I really enjoyed reading the book. The mindset approach provides a good reference framework for observing and understanding peoples' actions and approach. There are many interesting examples and very specific advice especially around raising children and teaching young people. There is even some valuable advice for couples.

Title: Understanding Emotion at Work
Author: Stephen Fineman

Title: Ethics
Author: Peter Singer

Title: Management 3.0: Leading Agile Developers, Developing Agile Leaders
Author: Jurgen Appelo

Author: Eric Ries

Title: The Alchemist
Author: Paulo Coelho

Title: The Power of Habit: Why We Do What We Do in Life and Business
Author: Charles Duhigg

Title: Zen and the Art of Motorcycle Maintenance
Author: Robert M. Pirsig
My Review: It's an amazing book, only four stars now, there is so much to digest, I'm sure my rating will go up once I understand more. Best modern philosophy book I've read.

Title: 50 Psychology Ideas You Really Need to Know
Author: Adrian Furnham

Title: The Upside of Irrationality: The Unexpected Benefits of Defying Logic at Work and at Home
Author: Dan Ariely

Title: Software for Your Head: Core Protocols for Creating and Maintaining Shared Vision
Author: Jim McCarthy

Title: Penguin's Hidden Talent
Author: Alex Latimer

Title: Smalltalk Best Practice Patterns
Author: Kent Beck
My Review: Another timeless classic and a great introduction to OO design in any language. SmallTalk is easy enough to read and understand. Fascinating to see how many original ideas from this book have surfaced many times over in Kent's later works.

Title: Practical Object-Oriented Design in Ruby: An Agile Primer
Author: Sandi Metz
My Review: One of the best books about design I have read. I found it eye-opening especially when it comes to the "messaging" view of OO. The fact that all the examples were in Ruby and I don't know Ruby almost at all was a huge benefit for me - I could concentrate on the principles and not on the details.

Title: C# in Depth
Author: Jon Skeet
My Review: Simply a must for every C# developer

Title: The Four Steps to the Epiphany: Successful Strategies for Startups That Win
Author: Steve Blank

Title: Delivering Happiness: A Path to Profits, Passion, and Purpose
Author: Tony Hsieh

Title: Agile Software Development with Scrum. Ken Schwaber and Mike Beedle
Author: Ken Schwaber
My Review: Yes, the initial book on Scrum so it's 5/5 for the thinking, the ideas, the change it started. The book itself, is not an easy read, is not very consistent and some of the thinking have now moved on, better to read software in 30 days these days methinks.

Title: The Phoenix Project: A Novel About IT, DevOps, and Helping Your Business Win
Author: Gene Kim
My Review: OK. So it's not The Goal. The inspiration and the parallels are obvious (even explicit) and the story is entertaining but personally I didn't find it as ground-breaking. It can be very good for people to get a basic understanding of the many concepts (flow, WIP, TOC, systems thinking, ...) The focus of the book is firmly on the operational side of IT and any parallels with software development must be taken with care.

Title: Abolishing Performance Appraisals: Why They Backfire and What to Do Instead
Author: Tom Coens
My Review: This has been one of the best books on the topic of people management and failures of the "traditional organisational management" that I have come across. This book is grounded in great expertise from people such as Peter Block, Ackoff, Deming... And it's not a straight critique of the existing systems but a deep analysis of the underlying assumptions and how they may be flawed and what could be the alternatives.

Title: The Halo Effect: And the Eight Other Business Delusions That Deceive Managers
Author: Philip M. Rosenzweig

Title: Understanding the Linux Kernel
Author: Daniel P. Bovet

Title: Commitment
Author: Olav Maassen

Title: Release It!: Design and Deploy Production-Ready Software (Pragmatic Programmers)
Author: Michael T. Nygard
My Review: I don't know why I only now got this book in my hands. It reveals so many things that I was missing in my development. It is full of aha! moments and realisations of the things that I have missed with great ideas of how I can improve. The book, in some aspects feels slightly dated - mainly with the technologies mentioned (evident focus on session state and relational databases) yet I can't think of a modern system that takes even a fraction of the applicable advice from the book regardless of technologies. And if you think agile - woven into the fabric of the book are great insights including the OODA loop (way before we had Lean Startup). A must read for every developer.

Title: The Inmates Are Running the Asylum: Why High Tech Products Drive Us Crazy and How to Restore the Sanity
Author: Alan Cooper
My Review: I have a really hard time rating this one. On the one hand it talks about Goal Driven, User-Centred design which is still deeply neglected and would mark a step change in user interaction and the ease of using our software. On the other hand I can't agree with the over-simplified picture of a software engineer homo logicus that is portrayed in the book. Surely BDUF is not the correct approach even to interaction design. Yet, we can save quite a bit on iterating if we do a decent chunk of it up front.

Title: The Five Dysfunctions of a Team: A Leadership Fable
Author: Patrick Lencioni
My Review: Great story with fantastic succinct examples. An easy read with very strong and important message and the presented model (or the 5 dysfunctions) are useful for working with teams. Some really good quotes as well, for example how fixing a team is similar to fixing a broken bone.

Title: Predictably Irrational: The Hidden Forces That Shape Our Decisions
Author: Dan Ariely
My Review: This book continues the topic of my interest - the psychology, biases and irrational behaviours. It's well written with lots and lots of well referenced and well described studies in behavioural economics. There are some experiments that repeat throughout the literature and some that I read about for the first time. Well worth a read for anyone curious about how and why we behave in many situations (in particular when and why are we honest and what makes us dishonest, how about our relationship to money and how money influences our choices and why two people can have fundamentally different opinion based on exactly the same facts).

Title: Pro Git
Author: Scott Chacon
My Review: Read Chapter 9. That's the real thing. Changed how I think about git dramatically.

Title: Becoming a Technical Leader: An Organic Problem-Solving Approach
Author: Gerald M. Weinberg
My Review: The best hones advice for aspiring leaders I have ever read. Plus tons of practical exercises.

Title: Effective Programming: More Than Writing Code
Author: Jeff Atwood

Title: Risk: The Science and Politics of Fear
Author: Daniel Gardner

Title: Dreaming in Code: Two Dozen Programmers, Three Years, 4,732 Bugs, and One Quest for Transcendent Software
Author: Scott Rosenberg

Title: Personal Kanban: Mapping Work | Navigating Life
Author: Jim  Benson
My Review: This is one of the best books I have recently read. Pragmatic, evidence based context sensitive approach to time management for everyone.

Title: The Lean Startup: How Today's Entrepreneurs Use Continuous Innovation to Create Radically Successful Businesses
Author: Eric Ries

Title: Secrets of Consulting: A Guide to Giving and Getting Advice Successfully
Author: Gerald M. Weinberg

Title: Peopleware: Productive Projects and Teams
Author: Tom DeMarco
My Review:
A very good book - easy read and I was rather surprised that some of the ideas were around for so long. It reads like a very modern and relevant book.

And now that I have read it again in the 2nd edition I like it even more - the final essays nicely expose many dysfunctions of organisations today.

Title: Who Is Agile
Author: Yves Hanoulle
Additional Authors: Andrea Chiou, Marcin Floryan, Peter Doomen
My Review: This is a great book full of interesting personal stories of people who have stumbled across Agile software development and are true practitioners of this approach.

Title: Thinking, Fast and Slow
Author: Daniel Kahneman

Title: Project Retrospectives
Author: Norman L. Kerth
My Review: The best book on retrospectives I have ever read. Full of practical exercises and some theoretical grounding with lots of references. This book is much better then the Agile Retrospectives book which now appears to me as a simple rip-off of this book.

Title: Kluge: The Haphazard Evolution of the Human Mind
Author: Gary F. Marcus
My Review: A nice journey through the evolutionary changes of our minds and their effects on our current thinking.

Title: Lean from the Trenches
Author: Henrik Kniberg
My Review: So it was OK indeed - a very nice story, some interesting insight but it didn't change my world. There is once excellent quote in the book about bugs and I recommend that you pick it up and read it for that one comment. Part 2 might be useful for someone new to Lean or Agile or systems thinking.

Title: Organizational Patterns of Agile Software Development
Author: James O. Coplien

Title: Scrumban: Essays on Kanban Systems for Lean Software Development
Author: Corey Ladas

Title: Incognito: The Secret Lives of the Brain
Author: David Eagleman
My Review: Full with fascinating examples of how our brains work and with interesting ideas on how we should interpret and stand with that knowledge.

Title: Liftoff: Launching Agile Teams & Projects
Author: Diana Larsen
My Review: I see the value of this book not in reading it - I found it almost a bit of a struggle to actually dry-read it. It's real value is in doing a lift-offs, in chartering with your teams and there are great, clear, concise instructions in the book how to achieve that - so just pick the book and take a team through it.

Title: Brilliant Mistakes
Author: Paul J.H. Schoemaker
My Review: When I started reading it I thought I made a wrong choice picking this book or that I will totally disagree with it, I still think it's too focused on the word mistake/error but I actually like the content.

Title: Why Plans Fail: Cognitive Bias & Decision Making
Author: Jim  Benson

Title: Complications: A Surgeon's Notes on an Imperfect Science
Author: Atul Gawande

Title: Key Management Models: Key Management Models
Author: Steven Ten Have
Additional Authors: Wouter ten Have, Frans Stevens, Marcel Van Der Elst, Fiona Pol-Coyne

Title: The Starfish and the Spider: The Unstoppable Power of Leaderless Organizations
Author: Ori Brafman

Title: Introducing Neuro-Linguistic Programming: Psychological Skills for Understanding and Influencing People
Author: Joseph  O'Connor

Title: Joel on Software
Author: Joel Spolsky

Title: Notes on Nursing
Author: Florence Nightingale
My Review: Amazing, so many years later and this book is still current and have some advice that many could do applying today. Also an interesting view into the Victorian England.

Title: The Checklist Manifesto: How to Get Things Right
Author: Atul Gawande
My Review: Loved the stories, like the ideas and I agree that checklists are underused.

Title: The Puritan Gift: Triumph, Collapse and Revival of an American Dream
Author: Kenneth Hopper
My Review: Certainly worth a read. A well written history of the American corporations since the days first settlers set foot on the new land. Gives context to better understand the ups and downs of the US economy, the different management schools of thought and their effect on corporations. Read where people like Sloan, Drucker, Deming, Taylor, Duran, Wren, Given, Sarasohn, Protzman and Polkinghorn among many others worked and what their ideas and contributions really were. Check what effect the American influence had on Japan and the appearance of Lean and TPS for example. Finally, see the 25 principles that every business today would do well to consider in their function.

Title: Java: A Beginner's Guide
Author: Herbert Schildt

Title: Waltzing with Bears: Managing Risk on Software Projects
Author: Tom DeMarco
My Review: Wow! This book talks so perfectly well about risk and uncertainty and exposes why we don't do it on IT projects and what are the repercussions. DeMarco and Lister really understand how and why agile works and this was in 2003. Most organisation as still way behind their thinking.

Title: Fearless Change: Patterns for Introducing New Ideas
Author: Mary Lynn Manns
My Review:
This is a first non-software patterns book that I read and for that it has given me a very interesting insight into the world of patterns and their wider appeal. I like the patterns listed in the book as they form a useful language to use when discussing change, at times, they feel too generic to give specific solutions and that's OK. Some mini-cases and examples of use felt a little bit weak, more a narrative that for me didn't always add much value.
I will be going back to the book.

Title: Switch: How to Change Things When Change Is Hard
Author: Chip Heath
My Review: Love the clear model, the numerous examples and interesting stories. It's well written, very practical and something that can really be applied in practice.

Title: Agile Testing: A Practical Guide for Testers and Agile Teams
Author: Lisa Crispin
Additional Authors: Janet Gregory, Mike Cohn, Brian Marick

Title: The Time Paradox: The New Psychology of Time That Will Change Your Life
Author: Philip G. Zimbardo

Title: Flow: The Psychology of Optimal Experience
Author: Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi
My Review: An effect of years of research into the psychology of happiness this book distils and presents in a compelling way our eternal search for order and meaning in life. I thoroughly enjoyed it especially its numerous concrete examples. This can truly transform your life.

Title: Living with Intensity
Author: Susan Daniels
Additional Authors: Michael M. Piechowski, Ellen D. Fiedler, Linda Kreger Silverman, Stephanie S. Tolan, Patricia Gatto-Walden, Annemarie Roeper, Elizabeth A. Meckstroth, Michele Kane, R. Frank Falk, Edward R. Amend, Sal Mendaglio, P. Susan Jackson
Publisher: Anodyne, Inc. DBA Great Potential Press, Inc.

Title: Implementing Beyond Budgeting: Unlocking the Performance Potential
Author: Bjarte Bogsnes

Title: The Happiness Hypothesis: Putting Ancient Wisdom to the Test of Modern Science
Author: Jonathan Haidt

Title: Flourish: A Visionary New Understanding of Happiness and Well-Being
Author: Martin E.P. Seligman

Title: Four Days with Dr Deming
Author: William J. Latzko
Additional Authors: David M. Saunders, W. Edwards Deming

Title: At Home: A Short History of Private Life
Author: Bill Bryson

Title: A Mind of Its Own: How Your Brain Distorts and Deceives
Author: Cordelia Fine
My Review: Even if it's ridden with language I did find challenging Cordelia presents the quirks of our brain in a really compelling way and clearly lays out the way our minds work beyond our cognition. Simply a must read if you want to understand how our minds work.

Title: Kluge: The Haphazard Construction of the Human Mind
Author: Gary F. Marcus

Title: The Paradox of Choice: Why More Is Less
Author: Barry Schwartz

Title: Purple Cow: Transform Your Business by Being Remarkable
Author: Seth Godin

Title: Agile Project Management with Scrum
Author: Ken Schwaber

Title: Getting to Yes: Negotiating Agreement Without Giving In
Author: Roger Fisher

Title: Who: The A Method for Hiring
Author: Geoff Smart

Title: The Pragmatic Programmer: From Journeyman to Master
Author: Andy Hunt

Title: Talent is Overrated: What Really Separates World-Class Performers from Everybody Else
Author: Geoff Colvin

Title: Crossing the Chasm: Marketing and Selling High-Tech Products to Mainstream Customers
Author: Geoffrey A. Moore

Title: Out of the Crisis
Author: W. Edwards Deming

Title: Crucial Confrontations: Tools for Resolving Broken Promises, Violated Expectations, and Bad Behavior
Author: Kerry Patterson
Additional Authors: Joseph Grenny, Ron McMillan, Al Switzler
My Review: Another very good book guiding how to handle difficult conversations with respect in a constructive way. It has an interesting model and one that can easily be put into practice. I still prefer the "Difficult Conversations" book as it provides more in-depth examples.

Title: Freakonomics: A Rogue Economist Explores the Hidden Side of Everything
Author: Steven D. Levitt

Title: Surely You're Joking, Mr. Feynman!: Adventures of a Curious Character
Author: Richard P. Feynman

Title: Chaos: Making a New Science
Author: James Gleick

Title: Made to Stick: Why Some Ideas Take Hold and Others Come Unstuck
Author: Dan Heath
My Review: A simple and potent framework for creating ideas that have a good chance to stick. Full of interesting and relevant stories, after all that's how you make the ideas stick, even if they are about sticky ideas.

Title: What the Dog Saw: And Other Adventures
Author: Malcolm Gladwell
My Review: Lots of really nice stories, not many with totally new ideas but a few gems nevertheless, like the title story. Well worth a read.

Title: To Engineer Is Human: The Role of Failure in Successful Design
Author: Henry Petroski
My Review: Learning from failure seems to work well for structural engineering. I'm not convinced it applies to software so well. Still the book is really interesting, well written and has interesting examples and good thoughts. I particularly liked the idea that if something has never failed it is most likely over-engineered.

Title: Shakespeare: The World as a Stage
Author: Bill Bryson

Title: The Life and Times of the Thunderbolt Kid: Travels through My Childhood
Author: Bill Bryson

Title: Notes from a Small Island
Author: Bill Bryson

Title: A Short History of Nearly Everything
Author: Bill Bryson

Title: God Bless You, Mr Rosewater
Author: Kurt Vonnegut Jr.

Title: Galápagos
Author: Kurt Vonnegut Jr.

Title: The Sirens of Titan
Author: Kurt Vonnegut Jr.

Title: Breakfast of Champions
Author: Kurt Vonnegut Jr.

Title: Slaughterhouse-Five, or The Children's Crusade: A Duty Dance with Death
Author: Kurt Vonnegut Jr.

Title: Cat's Cradle
Author: Kurt Vonnegut Jr.

Title: REST in Practice: Hypermedia and Systems Architecture
Author: Jim Webber

Title: The Black Swan: The Impact of the Highly Improbable
Author: Nassim Nicholas Taleb
My Review: Smart, challenging, thought-provoking book. In software development we have, for some time now, seen people waking up from the fallacies they have surrounded themselves with especial with regards to planning and estimation. To realise very similar mechanisms at play in economics is quite fascinating. There is still plenty I have to digest to begin a deeper understanding of Taleb's thinking but I now feel I am on the right path.

Title: Difficult Conversations: How to Discuss What Matters Most
Author: Bruce Patton
My Review: Now, just practice, practice, practice

Title: The Clean Coder: A Code of Conduct for Professional Programmers
Author: Robert C. Martin

Title: The Fifth Discipline: The Art & Practice of The Learning Organization
Author: Peter M. Senge
My Review: As Jurgen said, there are some nuggets of gold in this literary swamp ;) Part III is a must read. Brilliant.

Title: The Choice
Author: Eliyahu M. Goldratt

Title: Stiff: The Curious Lives of Human Cadavers
Author: Mary Roach

Title: Growing Object-Oriented Software, Guided by Tests
Author: Steve  Freeman

Title: Drive: The Surprising Truth About What Motivates Us
Author: Daniel H. Pink
My Review: Fascinating and frustrating. Frustrating for that such books need to be written and so many people do not get the Motivation 3.0 OS. Fascinating for all the research, experiments and knowledge about how our intrinsic and extrinsic motivation works.

Title: The Entrepreneur's Guide to Customer Development: A cheat sheet to The Four Steps to the Epiphany
Author: Brant Cooper

Title: Seeing the Forest for the Trees: A Manager's Guide to Applying Systems Thinking
Author: Dennis Sherwood

Title: I Hate Presentations: Transform the Way You Present with a Fresh and Powerful Approach
Author: James Caplin
My Review: Concise, relevant and modern. Great way to apply the Dreyfus model to creating presentations and getting much better at it. I like how it resonates with the work of Seth Godin.

Title: Agile Coaching
Author: Rachel Davies
My Review: Excellent guide to coaching full of all the essential basics, practical tips, real stories and useful references.

Title: The Machine That Changed The World
Author: James P. Womack

Title: Do Polar Bears Get Lonely?: And 101 Other Intriguing Science Questions
Author: New Scientist

Title: Design Patterns Explained: A New Perspective on Object-Oriented Design
Author: Alan Shalloway

Title: Don't Make Me Think: A Common Sense Approach to Web Usability
Author: Steve Krug

Title: Kanban: Successful Evolutionary Change for Your Technology Business
Author: David J. Anderson
My Review: Great as introduction to Kanban, good stories from traditional organisations, broad references but some advice lacked context.

Title: Freedom From Command And Control: A Better Way To Make The Work Work
Author: John Seddon
My Review: It's not possible to give a succinct summary of this excellent book - changes your thinking for ever and reveals all the sins of command & control.

Title: Forms That Work: Designing Web Forms for Usability
Author: Caroline Jarrett

Title: The Timeless Way of Building
Author: Christopher W. Alexander

Title: Information Dashboard Design: The Effective Visual Communication of Data
Author: Stephen Few

Title: Pomodoro Technique Illustrated
Author: Staffan Nöteberg
My Review: Great way to keep focus, eliminate the cost of context switching and actually achieve more in a day.

Title: Tribes: We Need You to Lead Us
Author: Seth Godin
My Review: You can lead. It is your choice. We need you. The only thing stopping you is fear - irrational fear. Break the status quo. Read this book.

Title: Founders at Work: Stories of Startups' Early Days
Author: Jessica Livingston
My Review: Good, varied stories, source of inspiration and insight into what starting a company and succeeding is really about.

Title: Groovy in Action
Author: Dierk König
Additional Authors: Andrew Glover, Paul King, Guillaume Laforge, Jon Skeet, James Gosling

Title: The Definitive Guide to Grails
Author: Graeme Rocher
My Review: As usual, too low information density for my liking and slightly too much noise but nevertheless a useful intro to Grails. Now I need to read the second edition.

Title: 97 Things Every Programmer Should Know: Collective Wisdom from the Experts
Author: Kevlin Henney

Title: Coders at Work: Reflections on the Craft of Programming
Author: Peter Seibel
My Review: Excellent insight into the work of some of the best programmers.

Title: I Want You to Cheat!: The Unreasonable Guide to Service and Quality in Organisations
Author: John Seddon

Title: The Structure of Scientific Revolutions
Author: Thomas S. Kuhn

Title: The Art of Computer Programming, Volumes 1-3 Boxed Set
Author: Donald Ervin Knuth

Author: Dave Meier

Title: Linchpin: Are You Indispensable?
Author: Seth Godin
My Review: Strange, I really feel like I'm already following Seth's advice yet still have far to go to do art! Read it to become an indispensable linchpin.

Title: Maverick: The Success Story Behind the World's Most Unusual Workplace
Author: Ricardo Semler
My Review: Excellent and inspiring book. Excellent not for its style (yet it reads very well) but primarily for the ideas. The best antidote to aged, obsolete yet still omnipresent command & control management style. Semco is the place you want to work in. I'm sorry Henry Ford, I'm sorry Frederick Winslow Taylor - you were just simply plain wrong.

Title: Smart and Gets Things Done: Joel Spolsky's Concise Guide to Finding the Best Technical Talent
Author: Joel Spolsky

Author: Kent Beck

Additional Authors: David Rice, Matthew Foemmel, Edward Hieatt, Robert Mee, Randy Stafford

Author: Jo Owen

Title: Open Space Technology: A User's Guide
Author: Harrison Owen

Title: Agile Product Management with Scrum: Creating Products That Customers Love

My Review: Really good guide to the role of Product Owner and approach to project management in Scrum.

Title: The Trusted Advisor
Author: David H. Maister
Additional Authors: Robert M. Galford, Charles H. Green
My Review: An invaluable amalgamation of essential techniques for trust building - very insightful, very challenging.

Author: Sayed Ibrahim Hashimi
My Review: It was useful. Good background on the subject and although some parts were too simplistic overall the coverage of the key aspects is good. I might keep using it for a while as a handy reference.

Title: Agile Modeling: Effective Practices for Extreme Programming and the Unified Process
Author: Scott W. Ambler

Title: Managing The Design Factory:  A Product Developer's Toolkit
Author: Donald G. Reinertsen

Title: Developing Products in Half the Time: New Rules, New Tools
Author: Preston G. Smith
My Review: Outstanding. This book is packed with rules and tools to accelerate product development. Without a single direct reference to IT this book explains the essence of Agile and Lean in a buzzword free way.

Title: Agile Retrospectives: Making Good Teams Great
Author: Esther Derby
My Review: Good, useful, great reference for activities that can be used during retrospectives.

Title: Essential Silverlight 3
Author: Ashraf Michail
My Review: Really useful, first good SL3 book I've read. It has list of really interesting technical insights and is actually an opportunity to learn something about graphics rendering in general as well as about SilverLight. Great introduction to this new technology that does not just repeat what is already in API documentation.

Title: Behind Closed Doors: Secrets of Great Management
Author: Johanna Rothman
My Review: Condensed and essential starter pack for any manager.

Title: Reversing: Secrets of Reverse Engineering
Author: Eldad Eilam

Title: Domain-Driven Design: Tackling Complexity in the Heart of Software
Author: Eric Evans

Title: Silverlight 3 Jumpstart
Author: David Yack
My Review: This looks very much like a rushed introduction to Silverlight 3. My edition sadly had several typos and errors and the style wasn't too good either. If felt like there were 2 pages of content for every 10 pages of text and sometimes there could have been a (UML) diagram that would explain the issue better than a textual description. However, the book was quick enough to read and amongst some noise there were actually some rather useful information included. I guess it's good enough to get a very basic understanding of Silverlight.
